1
00:00:10,698 --> 00:00:12,700
-[dogs barking]
-[train horn blowing]

2
00:00:14,452 --> 00:00:15,745
[Nicky sighs]

3
00:00:17,413 --> 00:00:18,998
[train passing]

4
00:00:20,374 --> 00:00:21,584
[Nicky moans softly]

5
00:00:24,628 --> 00:00:25,588
What did she look like?

6
00:00:25,671 --> 00:00:28,424
You know, for a second I thought,
"Is she gonna do the right thing

7
00:00:28,507 --> 00:00:29,550
and not bring this up?"

8
00:00:30,926 --> 00:00:34,138
It's fucked-up. Right?
Was it? It was fucked-up?

9
00:00:34,221 --> 00:00:37,308
Was cracking open a casket and stealing
a necklace off a dead body fucked-up?

10
00:00:37,391 --> 00:00:39,852
You know what, Morgan?
I'm gonna leave that one with you. Okay?

11
00:00:39,935 --> 00:00:41,645
Sorry, I just could not do it.

12
00:00:41,729 --> 00:00:43,522
-Like, I couldn't bring myself.
-I… I remember.

13
00:00:43,606 --> 00:00:45,483
-I was there as the sun was coming up.
-[groans]

14
00:00:45,566 --> 00:00:46,400
[Nicky] Okay?

15
00:00:46,484 --> 00:00:48,235
[Morgan sighs] Okay.

16
00:00:50,029 --> 00:00:51,447
[vehicle approaching]

17
00:00:52,239 --> 00:00:53,741
[metallic rattling]

18
00:00:55,117 --> 00:00:56,994
[Morgan sighs, groans]

19
00:00:57,078 --> 00:00:58,162
[grunts]

20
00:01:00,206 --> 00:01:01,457
[Nicky moans]

21
00:01:04,460 --> 00:01:05,503
[moans]

22
00:01:06,128 --> 00:01:08,255
[car doors slamming]

23
00:01:08,839 --> 00:01:10,049
[Nicky sighs]

24
00:01:11,175 --> 00:01:12,009
[clerk] Got it?

25
00:01:12,510 --> 00:01:13,344
Here.

26
00:01:13,844 --> 00:01:15,679
-[Nicky] Take it.
-[necklace clinks]

27
00:01:17,098 --> 00:01:20,184
-Why are you giving this to me for?
-What are you talking about?

28
00:01:20,267 --> 00:01:22,311
You wanted us to give it back.
We're giving it back.

29
00:01:22,394 --> 00:01:24,814
You're gonna give it back
to the person you stole it from.

30
00:01:24,897 --> 00:01:26,315
-[Nicky] What?
-Get in the truck.

31
00:01:26,398 --> 00:01:27,942
No, I'm not doing that again.

32
00:01:28,025 --> 00:01:30,111
-Oh, Nicky, get in the truck.
-Get in the truck.

33
00:01:30,194 --> 00:01:31,570
[Morgan] I'm so tired. Just get in.

34
00:01:31,654 --> 00:01:33,656
[frenetic music playing]

35
00:01:40,663 --> 00:01:42,414
[door rattles]

36
00:01:42,498 --> 00:01:43,374
Get out.

37
00:01:43,958 --> 00:01:45,084
-Get out!
-[Nicky] Okay.

38
00:01:45,167 --> 00:01:46,377
[door slams shut]

39
00:01:48,796 --> 00:01:50,172
-Go.
-[Nicky] Okay.

40
00:01:50,256 --> 00:01:52,258
-[Morgan] Get off of me.
-[Nicky] Please.

41
00:01:56,095 --> 00:01:57,179
[music ends]

42
00:01:57,263 --> 00:01:58,139
[birds chirping]

43
00:01:58,222 --> 00:01:59,056
What?

44
00:01:59,140 --> 00:02:01,016
Have you never been to a house before?

45
00:02:01,642 --> 00:02:03,936
-Ring the fucking bell!
-I don't know this person.

46
00:02:04,019 --> 00:02:04,937
-Ring the bell!
-Okay.

47
00:02:05,020 --> 00:02:05,938
-Stop.
-[doorbell rings]

48
00:02:06,021 --> 00:02:08,065
God, in the same time
you could've rang the bell.

49
00:02:08,149 --> 00:02:09,233
[Morgan exhales]

50
00:02:09,316 --> 00:02:11,026
[door creaking]

51
00:02:11,110 --> 00:02:12,903
[opera music playing]

52
00:02:14,196 --> 00:02:15,197
Come in.

53
00:02:17,449 --> 00:02:19,535
-[footsteps echoing]
-[door slams shut]

54
00:02:22,163 --> 00:02:23,080
[man] So…

55
00:02:24,540 --> 00:02:26,208
You dug up a grave.

56
00:02:26,292 --> 00:02:28,085
-[Morgan] Mm-hmm.
-Two, actually.

57
00:02:28,169 --> 00:02:29,879
[man] Incredible.

58
00:02:30,880 --> 00:02:31,714
Where is it?

59
00:02:32,423 --> 00:02:33,507
-[Morgan] Mmm.
-Psst!

60
00:02:33,591 --> 00:02:35,551
[whispers] Give him the fucking necklace.

61
00:02:35,634 --> 00:02:36,802
-[Morgan] Okay.
-All right.

62
00:02:36,886 --> 00:02:39,221
Eh, eh, eh, eh!
I'm… I'm not touching that.

63
00:02:39,305 --> 00:02:40,764
It's been on a dead woman.

64
00:02:40,848 --> 00:02:42,308
Did you clean it, Yusuf?

65
00:02:43,017 --> 00:02:44,351
Well, we came straight from--

66
00:02:44,435 --> 00:02:48,147
Then fucking clean it. I don't want
to touch a dead woman's germs.

67
00:02:48,230 --> 00:02:49,231
[Yusuf] Okay.

68
00:02:49,315 --> 00:02:50,316
[Nicky sighs]

69
00:02:50,399 --> 00:02:52,818
You've caused
quite a bit of trouble with this.

70
00:02:52,902 --> 00:02:55,446
I think the important thing here is
that you got the necklace back,

71
00:02:55,529 --> 00:02:57,948
and it's… it's very late,
and I would love to go home

72
00:02:58,032 --> 00:03:01,535
and shower off the smell
of an open casket before work, so I just…

73
00:03:01,619 --> 00:03:06,957
[man] Still… to steal
a necklace out of a locked case.

74
00:03:07,041 --> 00:03:10,753
Oh, well, the key was in the lock, so it's
not like the case was technically locked.

75
00:03:10,836 --> 00:03:13,756
You didn't tell me
the key was in the lock, Yusuf.

76
00:03:16,050 --> 00:03:19,261
[hesitates] She still broke in, so, um…

77
00:03:19,345 --> 00:03:21,513
[man] Well, did she break in

78
00:03:21,597 --> 00:03:24,850
or did she simply turn a key

79
00:03:24,934 --> 00:03:28,687
and take a $75,000 necklace

80
00:03:28,771 --> 00:03:32,024
out of a case you were
supposed to have your eyes on?

81
00:03:32,107 --> 00:03:34,485
-[Morgan] That's what I've been saying.
-[whispers] Let it go.

82
00:03:34,568 --> 00:03:37,947
Well, either way, she… broke in.

83
00:03:38,030 --> 00:03:40,658
Put the fucking kettle on.

84
00:03:40,741 --> 00:03:41,700
[softly] Okay.

85
00:03:43,285 --> 00:03:44,662
[footsteps fading]

86
00:03:45,663 --> 00:03:46,497
Come.

87
00:03:47,498 --> 00:03:48,666
Let's have a drink.

88
00:03:49,250 --> 00:03:51,418
[man] There we go. [exhales]

89
00:03:51,502 --> 00:03:52,795
[man grunts]

90
00:03:54,171 --> 00:03:57,007
Is this-- Is this alcohol
at 6:15 in the morning?

91
00:03:57,091 --> 00:03:58,968
[man] A reverend and a teacher,

92
00:03:59,051 --> 00:04:02,388
such upstanding members of the community,

93
00:04:02,471 --> 00:04:05,516
stealing jewels and digging up
their own grandmother.

94
00:04:05,599 --> 00:04:07,184
That's-- That's impressive.

95
00:04:07,268 --> 00:04:08,102
Okay.

96
00:04:08,769 --> 00:04:09,812
Huh.

97
00:04:10,437 --> 00:04:12,022
-[inhales]
-Oh, okay!

98
00:04:13,315 --> 00:04:14,775
I'd like to be friends.

99
00:04:15,818 --> 00:04:20,864
You know, you--
You seem like you have enough friends. I--

100
00:04:20,948 --> 00:04:21,991
[man] Here.

101
00:04:22,741 --> 00:04:25,577
A gift of gratitude.

102
00:04:28,163 --> 00:04:30,332
-Uh, that's not necessary.
-[man] Uh-uh-uh.

103
00:04:30,958 --> 00:04:31,875
I insist.

104
00:04:35,337 --> 00:04:36,547
Wow. Okay.

105
00:04:36,630 --> 00:04:38,799
-[Nicky] Is this a flip phone?
-Flip phones.

106
00:04:40,050 --> 00:04:41,760
This is really thoughtful. Thank you.

107
00:04:41,844 --> 00:04:44,388
So, now that we're friends,

108
00:04:44,471 --> 00:04:47,266
I might need a favor at some point.

109
00:04:47,349 --> 00:04:50,102
And friends do this for friends, right?

110
00:04:50,769 --> 00:04:52,813
[man inhales sharply] Okay.

111
00:04:55,024 --> 00:04:56,108
[speaks Russian]

112
00:04:57,651 --> 00:04:59,611
[man] Well, I guess that's that.

113
00:05:00,279 --> 00:05:01,280
[kettle whistling]

114
00:05:01,363 --> 00:05:02,990
Friends. [clicks tongue]

115
00:05:03,991 --> 00:05:07,036
When the phone rings, you answer it.

116
00:05:07,119 --> 00:05:09,121
[whistling intensifies]

117
00:05:09,204 --> 00:05:11,540
[opening theme music playing]

118
00:05:15,669 --> 00:05:16,795
[music ends]

119
00:05:16,879 --> 00:05:21,675
[Nicky] It is in these trying times
that I often find myself

120
00:05:21,759 --> 00:05:25,179
-[coughing]
-…thinking about the… the effects of fear.

121
00:05:26,263 --> 00:05:30,976
You know, fear has
this ability to… to call upon us

122
00:05:31,810 --> 00:05:32,853
out of the blue

123
00:05:32,936 --> 00:05:38,525
and… and coerce us into doing things
we never envisioned ourselves doing.

124
00:05:40,611 --> 00:05:43,864
In Proverbs, it is said,
"The fear of man lays a snare,

125
00:05:44,573 --> 00:05:47,826
but whoever trusts in the Lord is safe."

126
00:05:49,370 --> 00:05:50,788
Are we really, though?

127
00:05:51,997 --> 00:05:54,249
You know, if… if you… if you…
if you think about it,

128
00:05:54,333 --> 00:05:56,001
it does beg the question,

129
00:05:56,835 --> 00:05:58,629
"What are we doing?" You know?

130
00:05:58,712 --> 00:06:02,674
Is… is God punishing us for something?
Is this a test?

131
00:06:03,258 --> 00:06:06,178
What are we actually supposed to do

132
00:06:06,261 --> 00:06:10,849
in the face of, you know, I don't know,
let's go with "paralyzing terror"?

133
00:06:11,642 --> 00:06:14,978
You know, when the fear
has… has taken over our bodies,

134
00:06:15,062 --> 00:06:20,442
and we are just lying there at night
wondering what's happening next.

135
00:06:21,151 --> 00:06:22,069
[slow ticking]

136
00:06:22,152 --> 00:06:24,321
We're waking up with hot sweats.

137
00:06:24,405 --> 00:06:25,572
We're not eating.

138
00:06:27,116 --> 00:06:28,075
What do we do?

139
00:06:28,784 --> 00:06:30,202
[ticking accelerates]

140
00:06:30,702 --> 00:06:31,745
Hmm?

141
00:06:32,371 --> 00:06:34,248
[rhythmic ticking]

142
00:06:34,331 --> 00:06:35,582
Genuine question.

143
00:06:42,423 --> 00:06:43,507
[ticking ends]

144
00:06:43,590 --> 00:06:45,759
May the grace of Lord Jesus Christ
and the love of God

145
00:06:45,843 --> 00:06:48,512
and the fellowship of the Holy Spirit
be with all of you today.

146
00:06:50,180 --> 00:06:51,056
[Nicky] Okay.

147
00:06:51,140 --> 00:06:52,891
-[coughing]
-[murmuring]

148
00:06:53,892 --> 00:06:55,894
[birds chirping]

149
00:06:57,646 --> 00:06:59,148
-[door opens]
-[Morgan screams]

150
00:06:59,231 --> 00:07:02,276
It's ten o'clock. You might want
to get out of bed. Max is on his way over.

151
00:07:02,359 --> 00:07:04,862
I swear to God, the two of you, the drama.

152
00:07:04,945 --> 00:07:07,531
It's like Elizabeth Taylor
and Richard Burton over here

153
00:07:07,614 --> 00:07:09,116
if they both slept a lot.

154
00:07:09,199 --> 00:07:10,284
Why is he on his way over?

155
00:07:10,367 --> 00:07:12,453
He called me.
Apparently, your phone is dead.

156
00:07:12,536 --> 00:07:14,746
Honey, have you seen my blouse
with the little ties?

157
00:07:14,830 --> 00:07:18,041
It was in the laundry room,
then you did a wash and now it's gone.

158
00:07:18,125 --> 00:07:19,918
-I have a lot going on today.
-[Morgan moans]

159
00:07:20,002 --> 00:07:21,712
I'm declaring my candidacy.

160
00:07:21,795 --> 00:07:25,007
There's a photo that needs to be taken,
and now I have nothing to wear.

161
00:07:25,090 --> 00:07:29,219
Mom, you have no idea. The last couple
of days have been really intense for me.

162
00:07:29,303 --> 00:07:32,681
Yes, I'm sure that they have, honey.
[shouts] Oh, there it is!

163
00:07:32,764 --> 00:07:34,224
Oh, thank God.

164
00:07:34,308 --> 00:07:39,897
All right, I think that you need
to put on your big-girl pants

165
00:07:39,980 --> 00:07:41,607
and make up with your fiancé.

166
00:07:41,690 --> 00:07:43,484
Okay, so you're declaring your candidacy?

167
00:07:43,567 --> 00:07:46,153
That's what, you're, like,
shouting it to a roomful of people?

168
00:07:46,236 --> 00:07:49,740
It's too early for sarcasm, Morgan.
It's unattractive before noon.

169
00:07:49,823 --> 00:07:51,033
[doorbell rings]

170
00:07:51,116 --> 00:07:54,203
Be kind to him, honey.
He's a low-functioning person.

171
00:07:54,286 --> 00:07:56,663
-[Max] Morgan?
-[woman] Hey, Linda, I'm here with Max.

172
00:07:56,747 --> 00:07:57,706
[front door closes]

173
00:07:57,789 --> 00:08:00,501
[woman] Hope you have decaf,
because I've sworn off caffeine.

174
00:08:00,584 --> 00:08:04,379
[shouting] Annette, I didn't know
you were coming. I'm sure that I do.

175
00:08:04,463 --> 00:08:06,298
We'll be down in one second.

176
00:08:06,381 --> 00:08:08,467
[whispers] I don't have decaf.
Who has decaf?

177
00:08:08,550 --> 00:08:10,594
Why the fuck would he bring
his mom with him?

178
00:08:10,677 --> 00:08:13,055
Well, that's a really
good question, Morgan.

179
00:08:13,138 --> 00:08:14,181
[fridge door opens]

180
00:08:14,264 --> 00:08:16,767
Annette, I am so sorry.

181
00:08:16,850 --> 00:08:19,603
Max didn't mention that you were coming,

182
00:08:19,686 --> 00:08:21,939
or I would have got a coffee cake.

183
00:08:22,022 --> 00:08:24,816
Well, I hope this wasn't
too much of a surprise to you.

184
00:08:24,900 --> 00:08:26,735
No, not at all.

185
00:08:26,818 --> 00:08:30,113
Let's just hope that this chat
doesn't require coffee cake.

186
00:08:31,114 --> 00:08:33,367
Max, I really don't think
having this conversation

187
00:08:33,450 --> 00:08:35,786
in front of our mothers
is gonna get us through this.

188
00:08:35,869 --> 00:08:37,829
Okay, well, since you won't go
to therapy with me,

189
00:08:37,913 --> 00:08:41,333
I just think that them being here
will make us a lot nicer to each other.

190
00:08:42,209 --> 00:08:45,087
[Annette] So, Linda,
I-- I don't know about you,

191
00:08:45,170 --> 00:08:48,173
but if there's gonna be a marriage
between our families,

192
00:08:48,257 --> 00:08:50,634
and I'm gonna be dumping
some money into this thing,

193
00:08:50,717 --> 00:08:53,929
I want to know
that I'm not shoveling cash into a fire.

194
00:08:54,012 --> 00:08:57,849
Exactly. Ex-- Yeah, I've said that
almost every day. [inhales]

195
00:08:57,933 --> 00:09:00,394
This plate makes me want
to walk into traffic.

196
00:09:00,477 --> 00:09:04,022
Today was grocery day,
so please excuse whatever that is.

197
00:09:04,106 --> 00:09:06,900
No, seriously, it's more than enough.

198
00:09:06,984 --> 00:09:09,528
Max, baby, we've all got things to do.

199
00:09:09,611 --> 00:09:11,363
Yeah, okay, Mom. Um…

200
00:09:11,446 --> 00:09:12,739
Okay.

201
00:09:12,823 --> 00:09:15,659
Morgan, I'm sorry for calling you names.

202
00:09:15,742 --> 00:09:17,244
That wasn't kind.

203
00:09:17,869 --> 00:09:18,787
Yeah.

204
00:09:19,496 --> 00:09:20,372
[Morgan] Um…

205
00:09:21,039 --> 00:09:25,043
Yeah. So, obviously, I am sorry.
That's a given. [inhales] Um…

206
00:09:25,127 --> 00:09:27,462
See? You can't even
give me, like, a nice apology.

207
00:09:27,546 --> 00:09:30,549
Okay, well-- And then I'm gonna
say sorry now. I am sorry.

208
00:09:30,632 --> 00:09:33,635
Okay, kids, if we're gonna be useful
in this conversation,

209
00:09:33,719 --> 00:09:36,805
I think maybe a little bit
of context would be helpful.

210
00:09:36,888 --> 00:09:38,432
-I cheated on you too. There!
-Cheated?

211
00:09:38,515 --> 00:09:39,641
-What?
-You cheated?

212
00:09:39,725 --> 00:09:43,145
Well, to be fair,
it sounded like they both cheated.

213
00:09:43,228 --> 00:09:46,106
-Well, I kind-- I kind of cheated.
-What is "kind of cheated"?

214
00:09:46,189 --> 00:09:49,318
We didn't do, like, the whole thing.
It was like, we just did finger stuff.

215
00:09:49,401 --> 00:09:51,278
-Oh, Massimo!
-[Linda] Oh my God!

216
00:09:51,361 --> 00:09:52,279
It's not better.

217
00:09:52,362 --> 00:09:53,947
Oh, it's better than doing full penis.

218
00:09:54,031 --> 00:09:56,241
Do not say "penis" in front of Linda.

219
00:09:56,325 --> 00:09:59,328
-Morgan, what is he talking about?
-Just tell me how many times.

220
00:09:59,411 --> 00:10:02,581
Okay, well, how many times were you using
your fingers with some random person?

221
00:10:02,664 --> 00:10:04,541
All right, if we can't have
this conversation

222
00:10:04,625 --> 00:10:06,585
without referring
to "fingers" and "penises,"

223
00:10:06,668 --> 00:10:08,670
then, frankly, we don't need to be here.

224
00:10:08,754 --> 00:10:11,632
-Annette, I want to extend an apology…
-No. You don't need to.

225
00:10:11,715 --> 00:10:13,508
…to you on behalf of my daughter.

226
00:10:13,592 --> 00:10:16,261
No need. Max,
I raised you better than this.

227
00:10:16,345 --> 00:10:20,432
This is not going how Dr. Costa told me
that it would, Mom. I just… Morgan.

228
00:10:20,932 --> 00:10:24,603
You know how I feel about you, okay?
So I'm gonna go home,

229
00:10:24,686 --> 00:10:27,981
and just know that I'll be more than happy
to hear your key in that door,

230
00:10:28,565 --> 00:10:29,941
if that's what you still want.

231
00:10:31,443 --> 00:10:32,736
-Mama?
-No.

232
00:10:34,613 --> 00:10:37,032
Um, I'm sorry again
about the peanut butter.

233
00:10:37,115 --> 00:10:38,033
I hate peanut butter.

234
00:10:38,116 --> 00:10:39,576
I don't know if Max mentioned to you,

235
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:43,288
but I decided to run for mayor
since my mom passed.

236
00:10:43,372 --> 00:10:44,748
-I just have felt the need…
-What?

237
00:10:44,831 --> 00:10:46,124
…to be of use in a bigger way,

238
00:10:46,208 --> 00:10:49,127
but as you can see, it's made things
really hectic around here. [laughs]

239
00:10:49,211 --> 00:10:52,631
Oh, come on. Now you're making me
want to walk into traffic.

240
00:10:53,465 --> 00:10:57,260
I just, just backed Tom Donaldson.

241
00:10:57,928 --> 00:11:00,555
Tom Donaldson? The Jimmy John's guy?

242
00:11:00,639 --> 00:11:03,433
Yeah, leases out
a bunch of storefronts from me.

243
00:11:03,517 --> 00:11:05,727
-He just asked me last week.
-Yeah.

244
00:11:05,811 --> 00:11:08,271
-So Tom's running for mayor?
-Yeah.

245
00:11:08,355 --> 00:11:10,399
Because I wouldn't have thought
he had the time.

246
00:11:10,482 --> 00:11:12,776
He just seems so busy buying boats.

247
00:11:12,859 --> 00:11:15,070
-The man does have a lot of boats.
-Uh-huh.

248
00:11:15,153 --> 00:11:16,071
[clock chimes]

249
00:11:16,154 --> 00:11:20,742
You know, can I just say, though,
I think this is really good for you.

250
00:11:20,826 --> 00:11:23,704
-Oh, thank you, Annette. Thank you.
-I do.

251
00:11:23,787 --> 00:11:25,414
Appreciate that. [inhales]

252
00:11:25,997 --> 00:11:26,915
[door opens]

253
00:11:28,250 --> 00:11:29,626
[sighs]

254
00:11:29,710 --> 00:11:30,794
[door closes]

255
00:11:30,877 --> 00:11:31,712
Morgan.

256
00:11:31,795 --> 00:11:35,048
[techno music playing]

257
00:11:37,050 --> 00:11:38,135
[music ends abruptly]

258
00:11:38,218 --> 00:11:39,094
[gasps]

259
00:11:39,177 --> 00:11:41,847
[Tareq] I know trying on rental suits
isn't your favorite thing to do,

260
00:11:41,930 --> 00:11:43,557
but I dare you to look more miserable.

261
00:11:43,640 --> 00:11:46,893
Well, you're in luck.
I managed to find a 40 for your, um…

262
00:11:47,477 --> 00:11:48,687
-Cousin. Yeah.
-Oh.

263
00:11:48,770 --> 00:11:49,855
-Cousin?
-Yeah. He's, uh…

264
00:11:49,938 --> 00:11:51,148
-[Nicky] Yeah.
-We're close.

265
00:11:51,231 --> 00:11:52,149
[Nicky] Mm-hmm.

266
00:11:52,232 --> 00:11:53,567
Yeah, I can see that.

267
00:11:53,650 --> 00:11:55,819
-He's my date to an event next week.
-Mm-hmm.

268
00:11:55,902 --> 00:11:58,488
-I'm being honored for my queer activism.
-[clerk] Oh.

269
00:11:58,572 --> 00:12:01,199
-[Tareq] Yeah.
-I was at Stonewall for the riots.

270
00:12:01,742 --> 00:12:03,076
-Oh, wow.
-Wow.

271
00:12:03,160 --> 00:12:05,662
Uh… Thank you for your service.

272
00:12:05,746 --> 00:12:07,998
I was a closeted cop at the time.

273
00:12:08,957 --> 00:12:11,209
I'm convinced the shame gave me lupus.

274
00:12:11,293 --> 00:12:13,837
[cash register beeping, whirring]

275
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:15,839
Anyway, shirts and ties
are in the changing room.

276
00:12:15,922 --> 00:12:16,923
-Okay.
-Excuse me.

277
00:12:17,007 --> 00:12:18,592
-[Tareq] Yeah, thanks.
-Of course.

278
00:12:20,343 --> 00:12:21,928
-Am I him?
-What?

279
00:12:22,012 --> 00:12:24,681
Is that who I am to you?
Like some bad gay?

280
00:12:25,515 --> 00:12:27,058
Well, he has a wedding ring on, so…

281
00:12:27,142 --> 00:12:29,853
-Don't do that. That's not nice.
-You're worse. I'm kidding.

282
00:12:29,936 --> 00:12:31,563
No, I don't-- I don't find this funny,

283
00:12:31,646 --> 00:12:34,191
and it's not fun,
and I don't like lying to people,

284
00:12:34,274 --> 00:12:39,070
and I don't want to cosplay incest cousins
in some suit rental place.

285
00:12:39,154 --> 00:12:40,489
I don't want to get lupus.

286
00:12:40,572 --> 00:12:42,365
[whispers] Then stop lying for a day.

287
00:12:43,366 --> 00:12:45,577
I understand you not wanting me
to stay at your place

288
00:12:45,660 --> 00:12:48,246
or hold hands in a restaurant,
but we are two towns away.

289
00:12:48,330 --> 00:12:50,832
Brent doesn't give a fuck.
We don't know this person.

290
00:12:50,916 --> 00:12:53,126
-Please stop.
-Jesus, are these hives?

291
00:12:53,210 --> 00:12:55,378
-Nick, what is going on?
-Just grab me the shirt, please.

292
00:12:55,462 --> 00:12:57,839
-It's all over your chest.
-I know it is. It's a stress rash.

293
00:12:57,923 --> 00:12:58,799
All right?

294
00:12:58,882 --> 00:13:00,133
[softly] Okay, I'm sorry.

295
00:13:00,217 --> 00:13:02,344
-What can I do to help you relax?
-Absolutely nothing.

296
00:13:02,427 --> 00:13:05,055
[Brent] Doesn't look like the two of you
need my help. [chuckles]

297
00:13:05,138 --> 00:13:07,098
But if you do, I'll be waiting right here.

298
00:13:07,182 --> 00:13:08,350
[Tareq] Okay.

299
00:13:08,433 --> 00:13:09,810
-[Nicky] That's not funny.
-Okay.

300
00:13:09,893 --> 00:13:11,645
-Please just go deal with him. Please.
-Okay.

301
00:13:12,145 --> 00:13:14,898
-Brent, I think he needs a larger size.
-Yeah. This way.

302
00:13:16,733 --> 00:13:18,443
[phone ringing]

303
00:13:22,280 --> 00:13:24,199
-Fuck.
-[Tareq] Everything okay?

304
00:13:24,282 --> 00:13:26,409
Uh-huh. Yeah,
I'm just looking for my phone.

305
00:13:26,493 --> 00:13:27,953
[ticking resumes]

306
00:13:29,120 --> 00:13:31,122
[ringing continues]

307
00:13:34,125 --> 00:13:34,960
[quietly] Hello.

308
00:13:35,043 --> 00:13:35,961
[tense music playing]

309
00:13:36,044 --> 00:13:37,254
Yeah, this is he.

310
00:13:38,004 --> 00:13:39,172
[whispers] I can't hear you.

311
00:13:39,965 --> 00:13:43,385
I think there's-- There's bad reception.
You've given me a flip phone!

312
00:13:43,468 --> 00:13:45,262
[tense music continues playing]

313
00:13:46,179 --> 00:13:48,181
[tires screeching]

314
00:13:52,936 --> 00:13:53,979
[music ends]

315
00:13:54,855 --> 00:13:57,107
[Turkish music playing over speakers]

316
00:13:58,650 --> 00:14:00,277
What happened to your hand?

317
00:14:00,819 --> 00:14:03,572
What happened to your face,
you fucking bitch?

318
00:14:03,655 --> 00:14:06,074
Jesus, what the fuck is wrong with you?

319
00:14:06,157 --> 00:14:07,492
You are what's wrong.

320
00:14:08,410 --> 00:14:10,662
Like I have nothing else
to deal with in my life,

321
00:14:10,745 --> 00:14:14,082
now I have you two clowns
tied around my leg like a crime ball.

322
00:14:14,165 --> 00:14:16,084
-A what?
-A crime ball!

323
00:14:16,167 --> 00:14:19,588
The balls they tie to the legs
of criminals so they can't escape.

324
00:14:19,671 --> 00:14:21,172
The metal ball.

325
00:14:21,256 --> 00:14:22,382
Oh, a ball and chain.

326
00:14:22,465 --> 00:14:24,426
Whatever it is in English. I don't know.

327
00:14:24,509 --> 00:14:26,970
[Morgan] It's a ball and chain
in English. [clears throat]

328
00:14:27,470 --> 00:14:29,389
-Where are we going?
-Shut up!

329
00:14:29,472 --> 00:14:33,393
I'm sorry, but I need to know
what we're being asked to do.

330
00:14:33,476 --> 00:14:36,187
I hold a certain standing
in this community.

331
00:14:36,271 --> 00:14:37,105
[Yusuf whines]

332
00:14:37,188 --> 00:14:39,774
And there are limitations
on what I can participate in.

333
00:14:39,858 --> 00:14:42,944
[scoffs] Yeah? Tell that
to your dead grandma. Stupid.

334
00:14:46,197 --> 00:14:47,699
-[pulls hand brake]
-[engine stops]

335
00:14:47,782 --> 00:14:49,534
-[radio stops]
-[siren wailing in distance]

336
00:14:49,618 --> 00:14:50,535
[Yusuf] Okay.

337
00:14:50,619 --> 00:14:54,247
Take this. Go inside.
There's a man who's waiting for you.

338
00:14:54,331 --> 00:14:55,832
And don't fuck this up.

339
00:14:55,916 --> 00:14:57,334
Why can't you do it?

340
00:14:57,417 --> 00:15:00,003
[mocking] Because you two are like
pieces of white bread.

341
00:15:00,086 --> 00:15:02,881
Like dry vanilla cake
they feed the pigeons.

342
00:15:02,964 --> 00:15:05,884
That's why Ivan likes you. You can
get away with anything in this country.

343
00:15:05,967 --> 00:15:07,761
-Okay, so what…
-[phone ringing]

344
00:15:07,844 --> 00:15:09,930
…what kind of man are we meeting inside?

345
00:15:10,013 --> 00:15:11,765
-A man, okay?
-[ringing continues]

346
00:15:11,848 --> 00:15:14,267
Expecting you.
Just give him the cash and do the deal.

347
00:15:14,351 --> 00:15:15,810
-Okay.
-Wow.

348
00:15:15,894 --> 00:15:17,854
I don't know what deal he's talking about.

349
00:15:17,938 --> 00:15:19,940
-[Yusuf speaking Turkish]
-Can you let me out please?

350
00:15:20,440 --> 00:15:23,318
-I am suffocating… in there.
-[Morgan] Crazy mood today.

351
00:15:23,401 --> 00:15:24,402
Give me that.

352
00:15:24,486 --> 00:15:25,487
[car honking]

353
00:15:25,570 --> 00:15:27,489
-[Nicky] Ugh!
-Okay, yeah, I knew it was drugs.

354
00:15:27,572 --> 00:15:28,406
Drugs?

355
00:15:29,115 --> 00:15:30,992
Yeah, it's a drug deal. Hilare.

356
00:15:31,076 --> 00:15:32,369
How do you know it's a drug deal?

357
00:15:32,452 --> 00:15:35,914
Uh, because I was a struggling actress
in New York City for five years.

358
00:15:35,997 --> 00:15:39,167
-Yeah, it runs expensive.
-I didn't like a single word you said.

359
00:15:39,250 --> 00:15:42,379
What if we went in there
and just left out the back?

360
00:15:42,462 --> 00:15:43,713
Can you chill the fuck out?

361
00:15:43,797 --> 00:15:46,883
This is simple as long as you don't act
like a narc having an anxiety attack.

362
00:15:46,967 --> 00:15:49,010
-I'm not.
-You're quivering like a small dog.

363
00:15:49,094 --> 00:15:50,387
-I'm not quivering!
-You are.

364
00:15:50,470 --> 00:15:53,598
-There's a vibration coming off of you.
-So what if there's a vibration, okay?

365
00:15:53,682 --> 00:15:55,350
This isn't a natural thing for me.

366
00:15:55,433 --> 00:15:57,894
[exhales] Could you try
to center yourself for 20 minutes?

367
00:15:57,978 --> 00:16:00,772
-[Nicky] That's a dumb thing to say.
-Maybe 20 minutes. Not even.

368
00:16:01,272 --> 00:16:02,107
Hey. [exhales]

369
00:16:03,274 --> 00:16:04,818
Been waiting half an hour.

370
00:16:05,402 --> 00:16:06,236
[door slams]

371
00:16:06,319 --> 00:16:07,904
-Oh. No, sorry about that.
-No…

372
00:16:07,988 --> 00:16:09,197
Our driver's an idiot.

373
00:16:10,115 --> 00:16:11,366
Are we gonna do this?

374
00:16:11,950 --> 00:16:12,867
-Yeah.
-I--

375
00:16:13,618 --> 00:16:15,161
-[Nicky] Mm-hmm.
-Let's go.

376
00:16:18,331 --> 00:16:19,416
[suspenseful music playing]

377
00:16:19,499 --> 00:16:20,500
[elevator dings]

378
00:16:21,501 --> 00:16:22,544
Oh God.

379
00:16:23,211 --> 00:16:26,589
Uh… We're sure that there's, like, no way
we could do this above ground?

380
00:16:26,673 --> 00:16:28,133
-[Morgan sighs] Get in.
-Okay. Okay.

381
00:16:29,551 --> 00:16:32,137
[elevator door creaks]

382
00:16:36,725 --> 00:16:38,727
[suspenseful music continues playing]

383
00:16:47,736 --> 00:16:49,070
[music ends]

384
00:16:49,779 --> 00:16:51,906
-[soft banging noise]
-[water dripping]

385
00:16:57,245 --> 00:16:58,121
So?

386
00:17:00,081 --> 00:17:00,999
[man] You good?

387
00:17:01,750 --> 00:17:02,834
Am…

388
00:17:02,917 --> 00:17:03,960
Am I good?

389
00:17:04,044 --> 00:17:06,838
I don't-- I don't-- I don't know.
Morgan, am I-- Am I good?

390
00:17:06,921 --> 00:17:08,631
[gulps] Like, I'm good. Are you good?

391
00:17:09,591 --> 00:17:12,177
-As good as I can be.
-[Morgan] Good. Good.

392
00:17:12,260 --> 00:17:13,762
Okay. Uh…

393
00:17:15,555 --> 00:17:16,431
Am I--

394
00:17:16,514 --> 00:17:18,141
[whispers] Am I missing something?

395
00:17:18,224 --> 00:17:19,934
[phone ringing]

396
00:17:21,978 --> 00:17:22,812
[man] Yeah.

397
00:17:24,856 --> 00:17:27,150
All right. I have to take this.

398
00:17:27,233 --> 00:17:30,153
-[Nicky] Sure, of-- of course.
-No worries. Work comes first.

399
00:17:32,238 --> 00:17:34,365
-What is going on, Morgan?
-[whispers] I have no idea.

400
00:17:34,449 --> 00:17:37,702
-He's playing games. It's not cool.
-Aren't there supposed to be drugs?

401
00:17:37,786 --> 00:17:39,412
-Yeah, usually.
-Where are they?

402
00:17:39,496 --> 00:17:41,998
I don't know. I don't know.
I don't know. Just… Let me…

403
00:17:42,082 --> 00:17:43,750
[Nicky sighs] Is this a hit?

404
00:17:43,833 --> 00:17:45,460
-Huh?
-Is this a hit?

405
00:17:45,543 --> 00:17:46,836
-Have we seen too much?
-No.

406
00:17:46,920 --> 00:17:48,671
Because I don't want
this basement apartment

407
00:17:48,755 --> 00:17:50,298
to be the last thing I see before I die.

408
00:17:50,381 --> 00:17:52,926
-I'm being dead serious.
-Can I think for one second?

409
00:17:53,009 --> 00:17:55,178
-I've given you ten seconds.
-This needs to be said.

410
00:17:55,261 --> 00:17:58,640
-You would not last one day on Survivor.
-I don't watch Surviv--

411
00:17:59,265 --> 00:18:02,435
Okay, listen.
Are we buying drugs from you or not?

412
00:18:02,519 --> 00:18:03,394
Excuse me?

413
00:18:03,478 --> 00:18:05,105
Is this a fucking joke?

414
00:18:05,772 --> 00:18:07,941
No. No, it's fucking not.

415
00:18:08,024 --> 00:18:09,484
You think I sell drugs?

416
00:18:10,693 --> 00:18:11,569
Morgan?

417
00:18:11,653 --> 00:18:14,197
Why would you think that?
Because of the way I look?

418
00:18:14,280 --> 00:18:16,282
-No.
-I have never said that.

419
00:18:16,866 --> 00:18:20,161
You look at me and think,
"He has tattoos. He scares me."

420
00:18:20,245 --> 00:18:22,455
-"He must sell fucking drugs."
-No. No.

421
00:18:22,539 --> 00:18:24,207
We were told to come to--

422
00:18:24,290 --> 00:18:27,127
Told what? Wait, wait, wait, wait.
Someone told you I sell drugs?

423
00:18:27,210 --> 00:18:29,796
-Was it fucking Carmela, up in 2B?
-Was it Carmela?

424
00:18:29,879 --> 00:18:31,714
-Because she actually sells drugs.
-What?

425
00:18:31,798 --> 00:18:34,467
-I don't sell drugs… anymore.
-[Morgan] Okay.

426
00:18:34,551 --> 00:18:38,096
Hey, I'm a legitimate landlord
that takes pride in the apartments I rent.

427
00:18:38,179 --> 00:18:39,973
-All right?
-Right.

428
00:18:40,557 --> 00:18:42,058
Right, yeah. Um…

429
00:18:42,642 --> 00:18:44,519
-He's a landlord, Morgan.
-[sighs] Okay…

430
00:18:44,602 --> 00:18:46,062
He's renting us an apartment.

431
00:18:46,146 --> 00:18:50,108
Gotcha. Got it. There's been
a major misunderstanding here.

432
00:18:50,191 --> 00:18:54,946
[inhales deeply] When I was saying,
"We're gonna buy the drugs,"

433
00:18:55,029 --> 00:18:56,739
I was talking about,
like, "Oh, the drugs."

434
00:18:56,823 --> 00:18:58,408
I was being like, "Oh, like, the drugs."

435
00:18:58,491 --> 00:19:00,493
Like, the goods,
the property, the… you know,

436
00:19:00,577 --> 00:19:03,872
like, let's make a deal
type of, like, "Show me the money."

437
00:19:03,955 --> 00:19:05,331
[both] Show me the money.

438
00:19:05,415 --> 00:19:09,919
Yes, like, when you are making a deal--
It doesn't matter-- We will take it.

439
00:19:10,503 --> 00:19:12,213
-We'll take it?
-We'll take the place.

440
00:19:12,297 --> 00:19:15,675
That's cute. If you think I'm renting you
this apartment, you're fucking crazy.

441
00:19:15,758 --> 00:19:17,177
Oh God.

442
00:19:17,260 --> 00:19:22,182
Uh, I, for one, think that you have done
a wonderful job with this space.

443
00:19:27,645 --> 00:19:31,191
[Natalie] I think you're really gonna like
the design for the campaign website.

444
00:19:31,274 --> 00:19:33,484
We just might need to hire
a freelance web designer,

445
00:19:33,568 --> 00:19:36,404
but I have a clear design aesthetic,
so it shouldn't take that long.

446
00:19:36,487 --> 00:19:38,656
[Linda] I don't know, hon,
it sounds expensive.

447
00:19:38,740 --> 00:19:40,658
-Also, lawn signs have been ordered.
-Mmm.

448
00:19:40,742 --> 00:19:42,994
Yeah! And I know you thought
the pins were cheesy.

449
00:19:43,077 --> 00:19:44,996
-But I think they could go a long way.
-Hi, Kurt.

450
00:19:45,079 --> 00:19:47,290
[Natalie] Kids putting them
on their backpacks, et cetera.

451
00:19:47,373 --> 00:19:49,876
Speaking of kids,
I do think we should be getting involved

452
00:19:49,959 --> 00:19:52,295
with the PTA organizations
at our local elementary schools.

453
00:19:52,378 --> 00:19:53,671
-Well…
-[Natalie inhales]

454
00:19:53,755 --> 00:19:56,758
Just considering our focus
is on community and family,

455
00:19:56,841 --> 00:19:59,135
that could be a great place
to start meeting folks.

456
00:19:59,219 --> 00:20:00,178
[hesitantly] Yeah.

457
00:20:01,012 --> 00:20:02,430
[Linda exhales sharply]

458
00:20:02,513 --> 00:20:07,644
[inhales] I was wondering
if maybe we should hit pause.

459
00:20:07,727 --> 00:20:09,604
[inhales] On what?

460
00:20:09,687 --> 00:20:13,566
On the campaign.
Take a minute to risk assess.

461
00:20:14,651 --> 00:20:17,237
Hm. I'm sorry, what--
What are you talking about?

462
00:20:17,320 --> 00:20:21,074
Well, honey, it's just that I have
a really busy few months coming up,

463
00:20:21,157 --> 00:20:24,911
what, with wrapping up
Nonna's estate and the store.

464
00:20:24,994 --> 00:20:28,539
Do I really have the time
to service the town

465
00:20:28,623 --> 00:20:30,875
in the way that they would want from me?

466
00:20:30,959 --> 00:20:33,086
Is this about Tom Donaldson?

467
00:20:33,169 --> 00:20:34,754
He's a millionaire.

468
00:20:34,837 --> 00:20:38,174
He has an Ivy League degree.
I'm a college dropout.

469
00:20:38,258 --> 00:20:39,634
Honey, I sell shovels.

470
00:20:39,717 --> 00:20:41,886
He'll obliterate us
in front of the whole town,

471
00:20:41,970 --> 00:20:44,889
and I don't think that I have
a thick enough skin right now

472
00:20:44,973 --> 00:20:46,933
for that kind of humiliation.

473
00:20:47,016 --> 00:20:49,060
[breathes deeply]

474
00:20:50,979 --> 00:20:51,854
I see.

475
00:20:54,983 --> 00:20:55,858
[quietly] Okay.

476
00:20:58,319 --> 00:20:59,696
[clears throat sharply]

477
00:20:59,779 --> 00:21:01,364
-Honey.
-[objects clattering]

478
00:21:01,447 --> 00:21:02,824
Now, what is going on?

479
00:21:02,907 --> 00:21:05,702
[Natalie] Oh, nothing.
